The paper proposes a reinforcement learning algorithm that learns from both demonstrations and interactions with the environment. This falls under the broad category of machine learning, specifically reinforcement learning. The paper also mentions the use of deep neural networks for policy and Q-function approximation, which suggests a focus on deep learning. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely sub-category. 

The paper also deals with learning from imperfect or noisy demonstrations, which is a common problem in reinforcement learning. This suggests a focus on artificial intelligence and robotics, which are covered by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.RO (Robotics). 

The paper also mentions the evaluation of the algorithm on driving games, which suggests a focus on computer vision and image processing, covered by cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Finally, the paper deals with the joint optimization of divergent losses, which suggests a focus on control systems and optimization, covered by cs.SY (Systems and Control).
